. Political Time and Policy Coalitions: Structure and Agency in Presidential Power -- tChapter 14. The Institutional Face of Presidential Power: Congressional Delegation of Authority to the President -- tChapter 15. Hitting the Ground Running: The Politics of Presidential Appointments in Transition -- tPart 5. The Potential for Leadership -- tChapter 16. Presidential Power and the Potential for Leadership -- tChapter 17. Presidential Polling and the Potential for Leadership -- tChapter 18. The President as Message and Messenger: Personal Style and Presidential Communications -- tChapter 19. The Limits of the Transformational Presidency -- tPart 6. Conclusion: Forging the Presidency for the 21st Century -- tChapter 20. A Preachment from Retirement -- tChapter 21. The Impeachment of President Bill Clinton: Background -- tChapter 22. The “Hard Case” for Presidential Power: Impeachment Politics and Law -- tChapter 23. Conclusion: Presidential Power, Institutions, and Democracy -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRichard Neustadt's seminal work Presidential Power: The Politics of Leadership has endured for nearly four decades as the core of academic study of the American presidency. Now, building on and challenging many of the arguments in Neustadt's work, Presidential Power: Forging the Presidency for the Twenty-first Century offers reflections and implications from what we have learned about presidential power as the new century dawns. These essays—including a new contribution by Neustadt himself—forge a solid reexamination of Neustadt's Presidential Power that address questions raised but not resolved by his work. A notable aspect of this volume's analysis is the transformed institution of the presidency in the wake of the impeachment hearings of the country's last twentieth-century president, Bill Clinton. From the portrayal of presidents as persuaders to the politics of presidential transitions, each of the constituent essays in this volume provides an engaging look at the state of the American presidency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Executive Branch.2bisacsh1 aCameron, Charles M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickinson, Matthew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards iii, George C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpstein, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunnell, John G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeith, Diane J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHritzuk, Natasha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Lawrence R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Lawrence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKumar, Martha Joynt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKumar, Martha Joynt, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLieberman, Robert C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLink, Michael W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayer, Kenneth R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCarty, Nolan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Halloran, Sharyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeterson, Mark A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPious, Richard M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreston, Thomas, econtributor